            </ul>
          </aside>

          <!-- Section 2: What is RRM? -->
          <h2 id="what-is-rrm">What Is Restorative Reproductive Medicine?</h2>

          <p><strong>Restorative Reproductive Medicine (RRM) is a medical discipline that identifies and treats the root causes of reproductive health conditions.</strong> It works cooperatively with the body rather than against it. Where conventional approaches often default to suppressive medications that mask symptoms or assisted reproductive technologies that bypass natural function entirely, RRM uses standard and advanced diagnostic tools to find the actual cause, whether hormonal, anatomical, inflammatory, or metabolic, and restore the body to healthy function.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1b">1</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM is not alternative medicine. It is not faith-based medicine. RRM physicians are board-certified OBGYNs, reproductive endocrinologists, and family physicians who use the same tools as any other specialist: bloodwork, imaging, surgery, and pharmacology. The difference is in how and when those tools are applied. Every intervention is timed to a woman's individual cycle and targeted to a specific diagnosis.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>Conditions commonly addressed include endometriosis, polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), unexplained infertility, recurrent miscarriage, ovulatory dysfunction, pelvic pain, and hormonal imbalances. Treatment benefits extend beyond fertility. Women who are not trying to conceive still benefit from diagnosis and treatment of conditions that affect long-term health.</p>

          <h3>How RRM Works: Three Core Principles</h3>

          <p>RRM follows a diagnostic-first approach built on three principles:</p>

          <ol>
            <li><strong>Identify the root cause.</strong> The evaluation begins with cycle charting using a validated fertility awareness-based method such as the Creighton Model FertilityCare System. The chart provides daily biomarker data that reveals hormonal patterns invisible to a single blood draw or office visit. From there, RRM physicians order targeted bloodwork timed to specific cycle days, advanced imaging (pelvic ultrasound, sonohysterography, hysterosalpingography), and, when indicated, diagnostic laparoscopy. Semen analysis is standard for every couple. The goal is a complete, specific diagnosis, not an empiric guess.</li>
            <li><strong>Treat the underlying condition.</strong> Treatment is matched to the diagnosis. Hormonal support (such as bio-identical progesterone timed to the luteal phase), medication to address thyroid, metabolic, or inflammatory factors, nutritional optimization, and surgical intervention (such as excision surgery for endometriosis) are all part of the toolkit. Protocols are individualized and adjusted cycle by cycle based on the patient's chart and lab response.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7">7</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>Restore natural function.</strong> The goal is not to bypass the reproductive system but to optimize it. RRM addresses the disease itself so the body can function as designed. This means couples can achieve in vivo conception when possible. Even when pregnancy is not the goal, treating the root cause improves quality of life, prevents disease progression, and supports long-term health.</li>
          </ol>

          <h3>What RRM Is Not</h3>

          <p>Common misconceptions deserve direct answers:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>"RRM is only for Catholics."</strong> No. RRM is practiced by physicians of varied backgrounds and serves patients of all faiths and no faith. The science does not depend on any religious framework. Both Catholic and non-Catholic patients seek RRM because they want a thorough diagnostic workup and cause-based treatment.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2b">2</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>"RRM is anti-IVF."</strong> RRM is its own medical paradigm. It does not define itself in opposition to any other approach. RRM physicians focus on what they can diagnose and treat. The question RRM asks is: "Why can't this couple conceive?" Not: "How can we bypass the problem?"</li>
            <li><strong>"RRM is unscientific."</strong> RRM is supported by peer-reviewed research published in journals including <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>, <em>The Journal of the American Board of Family Medicine</em>, <em>Frontiers in Medicine</em>, and the <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em>. The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Academy Research Library</a> indexes over 3,000 peer-reviewed publications.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3b">3</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4b">4</a></sup></li>
          </ul>

          <aside class="callout-provider">
            <h3>For Healthcare Professionals</h3>
            <p>RRM integrates into existing OBGYN practice. Board-certified physicians can pursue additional training through IIRRM credentialing, NaProTechnology fellowship programs, or CME courses at <a href="/courses/">RRM Academy</a>. The approach builds on standard diagnostic and surgical skills with specialized cycle-based evaluation methods.</p>
          </aside>

          <!-- Section 3: History -->
          <h2 id="history">A Brief History of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</h2>

          <p>Restorative reproductive medicine did not emerge overnight. It grew from decades of clinical observation, scientific research, and a persistent question: what is the menstrual cycle actually telling us?</p>

          <h3>The Foundations: Fertility Awareness Research (1950s-1970s)</h3>

          <p>In the 1950s and 1960s, Drs. John and Evelyn Billings in Melbourne, Australia, developed the Billings Ovulation Method. Their research established that cervical mucus patterns reflect underlying hormonal activity and can reliably identify the fertile window. This was a foundational insight: the female body produces observable, measurable biomarkers that track its reproductive status in real time.<sup><a href="#ref-8" id="cite-8">8</a></sup></p>

          <p>Building on this work, Dr. Thomas Hilgers at Creighton University developed the Creighton Model FertilityCare System (CrMS) beginning in 1976. CrMS standardized the observation and recording of cervical mucus biomarkers into a rigorous, teachable system. But Hilgers saw something more than a family planning tool. He recognized that the daily charting data revealed patterns that correlated with specific reproductive disorders. Abnormal bleeding patterns, shortened luteal phases, and absent or disrupted mucus cycles were not random. They were diagnostic signals.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9">9</a></sup></p>

          <h3>NaProTechnology and the Pope Paul VI Institute (1980s-1990s)</h3>

          <p>In 1985, Dr. Hilgers founded the Pope Paul VI Institute for the Study of Human Reproduction in Omaha, Nebraska. Over the following decades, the institute conducted the only known prospective, real-time studies tracking women's hormones throughout their cycles.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2c">2</a></sup> This research transformed understanding of the luteal phase, progesterone dynamics, and ovulatory function.</p>

          <p>The result was NaProTechnology (Natural Procreative Technology): a medical and surgical system that uses CrMS charting data to guide diagnosis and treatment. Physicians trained at the Pope Paul VI Institute learned to read the cycle chart the way a cardiologist reads an EKG, detecting patterns that pointed to specific conditions: endometriosis, PCOS, luteal phase deficiency, ovulatory dysfunction, and hormonal imbalance. They then applied targeted medical and surgical interventions timed to the cycle.</p>

          <p>NaProTechnology represented a paradigm shift. Instead of suppressing the cycle with hormonal medications or bypassing it with laboratory conception, physicians worked with the cycle to restore healthy function.</p>

          <h3>Expanding the Field (2000s-2010s)</h3>

          <p>In 2008, the International Institute for Restorative Reproductive Medicine (IIRRM) was founded to formalize training, credentialing, and research collaboration across the growing field. The IIRRM brought together physicians from multiple countries who practiced cycle-based, cause-oriented reproductive medicine, whether through NaProTechnology or other emerging protocols.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1c">1</a></sup></p>

          <p>Several additional approaches developed during this period:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>FEMM (Fertility Education and Medical Management)</strong> introduced a hormonal health protocol that combined fertility charting with medical management of hormonal conditions, working closely with the Reproductive Health Research Institute.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6b">6</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>NeoFertility,</strong> developed by Dr. Phil Boyle in Dublin, expanded RRM treatment options to address autoimmune and inflammatory conditions alongside hormonal imbalances, demonstrating live birth rates comparable to IVF at a fraction of the cost.<sup><a href="#ref-10" id="cite-10">10</a></sup></li>
            <li><strong>FACTS About Fertility,</strong> co-founded by Dr. Marguerite Duane, began educating medical students and physicians about the evidence supporting FABMs and RRM, filling a gap in standard medical training.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5b">5</a></sup></li>
          </ul>

          <p>The <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em> launched to provide a dedicated peer-reviewed venue for RRM research, and programs like Dr. Patrick Yeung's RESTORE Center for Endometriosis advanced surgical excision techniques that achieved repeat-surgery rates of just 2.5% over ten years, compared to 40 to 60% within one to two years after ablation.<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11">11</a></sup></p>

          <h3>Mainstream Recognition (2025-Present)</h3>

          <p>In 2025, RRM entered the national policy conversation. Arkansas became the first U.S. state to mandate insurance coverage for restorative reproductive medicine. The RESTORE Act (H.R. 3589) was introduced in the U.S. Congress to expand access to RRM treatments. The Heritage Foundation published a comprehensive report on RRM as an alternative to assisted reproductive technology.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12">12</a></sup></p>

          <p>Major media outlets covered RRM for the first time, including <em>The New York Times</em>, STAT News, <em>The Cut</em>, <em>The 19th</em>, MedPage Today, and OSV News. Professional societies including ACOG and ASRM published their own analyses of the field, signaling that RRM had become too significant to ignore.</p>

          <p>Today, RRM-trained physicians practice on every continent except Antarctica.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2d">2</a></sup> The field continues to grow as research advances, training programs expand, and more couples and physicians discover a medical approach that asks the fundamental question: what is causing this, and how do we fix it?</p>

          <!-- Section 4: Diagnosis -->
          <h2 id="diagnosis">How RRM Diagnosis Works</h2>

          <p>Most couples who struggle with infertility receive a limited diagnostic workup. Standard practice often involves a basic hormone panel, a semen analysis, and imaging, followed by referral to IUI or IVF within three to six months, frequently without a complete diagnosis.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12b">12</a></sup> The label "unexplained infertility" is assigned to roughly 15 to 30% of couples, but RRM physicians view this label as "not yet diagnosed." In their experience, a cause almost always exists. It simply has not been found yet.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5c">5</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM takes a different approach. The diagnostic workup is systematic, thorough, and timed to the individual woman's cycle. It evaluates both partners. And it aims for a specific diagnosis before any treatment begins.</p>

          <h3>1. Cycle Charting: The Diagnostic Foundation</h3>

          <p>Every RRM evaluation starts with the cycle chart. A woman learns a validated fertility awareness-based method (such as the Creighton Model, Marquette Method, or FEMM) and records daily biomarker observations: cervical mucus patterns, bleeding characteristics, and in some methods, basal body temperature or urinary hormone levels.</p>

          <p>This chart provides something no single blood test or ultrasound can: a continuous, real-time record of hormonal activity across the entire cycle. The cycle chart to an RRM physician is like an EKG to a cardiologist. It reveals patterns. A shortened luteal phase. Absent or disrupted mucus. Premenstrual spotting. Abnormal bleeding. Each pattern points toward specific conditions.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2e">2</a></sup></p>

          <p>Dr. Thomas Hilgers, who pioneered this approach, described the realization that launched NaProTechnology: women's charts "had similar patterns to them when they had abnormalities in their health care. He understood that the charts were actually telling him something, and he was able to coordinate medical care with the charting system."<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9b">9</a></sup></p>

          <h3>2. Targeted Hormonal Panels</h3>

          <p>Standard fertility workups often check progesterone on a single calendar day, typically cycle day 21. This assumes a 28-day cycle with ovulation on day 14. Many women do not fit this template. If ovulation occurs earlier or later, the day-21 draw misses the target entirely, producing misleading results.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6c">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM solves this by anchoring bloodwork to the ovulatory event identified on the chart, not a calendar estimate. The targeted hormonal panel is drawn on specific post-peak days (typically peak +3, +5, +7, +9, and +11) to map progesterone and estradiol across the full luteal phase. This serial measurement reveals deficiencies that a single draw would miss.</p>

          <aside class="callout-provider">
            <h3>For Healthcare Professionals</h3>
            <p>The targeted hormonal panel in RRM includes: peak +3/+5/+7/+9/+11 progesterone, estradiol, LH, FSH, thyroid panel (TSH, free T3, free T4, TPO antibodies), fasting insulin, DHEA-S, and testosterone. Timing is anchored to the ovulatory event identified through the patient's cycle chart, not a calendar estimate.</p>
          </aside>

          <h3>3. Advanced Imaging</h3>

          <p>Structural evaluation is a standard part of the RRM workup. Pelvic ultrasound assesses ovarian morphology (including signs of PCOS), uterine anatomy, and follicular development. Sonohysterography (SIS) evaluates the uterine cavity for polyps, fibroids, or adhesions. Hysterosalpingography (HSG) confirms tubal patency. These imaging studies help identify anatomical factors that contribute to infertility or pain.</p>

          <h3>4. Diagnostic Laparoscopy</h3>

          <p>Endometriosis remains the most underdiagnosed reproductive condition. The average time from symptom onset to diagnosis is seven to twelve years.<sup><a href="#ref-13" id="cite-13">13</a></sup> One reason: diagnostic surgery is underused. Many physicians rely on imaging alone, but endometriosis is frequently invisible on ultrasound, especially in early stages.</p>

          <p>Diagnostic laparoscopy is the gold standard for confirming endometriosis. In the hands of a trained excision surgeon, it is both diagnostic and therapeutic. The disease is visualized, biopsied for pathologic confirmation, and excised in the same procedure. According to Dr. Patrick Yeung's ten-year database, over 90% of women presenting with pain and infertility have endometriosis, and many of them had previously been told their infertility was "unexplained."<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11b">11</a></sup></p>

          <h3>5. Male Factor Evaluation</h3>

          <p>RRM evaluates both partners from the start. Infertility involves a male factor in approximately 30% of cases and combined male-female factors in another 40%.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5d">5</a></sup> A comprehensive semen analysis is standard. When abnormalities are found, restorative andrology addresses the underlying cause: hormonal imbalances, varicocele, infections, or metabolic factors. The goal is to restore sperm quality, not bypass the problem.</p>

          <p>This differs significantly from the conventional approach, where male factor infertility is often addressed by shifting the entire treatment burden onto the woman through intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI), an advanced laboratory procedure that fertilizes an egg with a single sperm. ICSI bypasses the male condition entirely without treating it.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12c">12</a></sup></p>

          <h3>The Diagnostic Difference</h3>

          <p>The result of this systematic workup is a specific, actionable diagnosis for the couple, not a label of "unexplained infertility" and a referral to bypass the problem. Treatment follows from diagnosis. Every medication, every surgical decision, every protocol adjustment is tied to what the data shows. This is the core of cause-based medicine: find the disease, treat the disease, restore the function.</p>

          <!-- Section 5: FABMs -->
          <h2 id="fabms">Fertility Awareness-Based Methods (FABMs) Explained</h2>

          <p>Fertility awareness-based methods are most widely known as tools for family planning. They help couples identify the fertile window to achieve or avoid pregnancy. But within RRM, FABMs serve a fundamentally different purpose: they are clinical diagnostic instruments.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6d">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>This is the content gap that most health resources miss. Organizations like ACOG and Planned Parenthood frame FABMs purely as contraception. But for RRM physicians, the daily biomarker data from a well-charted cycle is the single most important diagnostic tool available. It reveals what is happening hormonally across the entire cycle, not just on the day a patient happens to visit the office.</p>

          <h3>FABMs as Diagnostic Tools</h3>

          <p>The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists has recognized the menstrual cycle as a "vital sign" since 2015, alongside body temperature, pulse rate, respiratory rate, and blood pressure.<sup><a href="#ref-14" id="cite-14">14</a></sup> A cycle chart captures this vital sign in detail. It records daily observations, cervical mucus characteristics, bleeding patterns, and (depending on the method) basal body temperature and urinary hormone levels, creating a continuous hormonal profile.</p>

          <p>When trained physicians read this data, patterns emerge. Limited cervical mucus may indicate low estrogen. A short luteal phase (fewer than 11 days from ovulation to menstruation) suggests inadequate progesterone. Premenstrual spotting or tail-end brown bleeding can signal hormonal imbalance. Long or irregular cycles may point to PCOS or ovulatory dysfunction. These are not vague clues. They are specific biomarker signals that direct further testing.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9c">9</a></sup></p>

          <p>Without chart data, the physician cannot time bloodwork correctly. A progesterone draw on the wrong cycle day produces a meaningless number. With chart data, every lab order is precise. That precision is what makes RRM diagnosis fundamentally different from standard fertility evaluation.</p>

          <h3>Major FABMs Used in RRM</h3>

          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Method</th>
                  <th>Biomarkers Tracked</th>
                  <th>Diagnostic Utility</th>
                  <th>Training Required</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Creighton Model (CrMS)</td>
                  <td>Cervical mucus observations (standardized scoring system)</td>
                  <td>Foundation for NaProTechnology diagnosis; most extensively studied for medical applications</td>
                  <td>FertilityCare Practitioner certification</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Marquette Method</td>
                  <td>Urinary hormones (via ClearBlue or Mira monitor), optional cervical mucus and temperature</td>
                  <td>Objective hormonal pattern identification; strong for women with ambiguous mucus signs</td>
                  <td>Marquette-trained instructor</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>FEMM</td>
                  <td>Hormonal biomarkers and cervical mucus</td>
                  <td>Hormonal health protocol with integrated medical management referral pathway</td>
                  <td>FEMM-trained provider</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Billings Ovulation Method</td>
                  <td>Cervical mucus observations</td>
                  <td>Ovulation confirmation, cycle pattern recognition; strong for continuous mucus and irregular cycles</td>
                  <td>Billings-trained instructor</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>SymptoThermal Methods</td>
                  <td>Basal body temperature, cervical mucus, optional cervical position</td>
                  <td>Multi-biomarker cross-checking; temperature provides objective ovulation confirmation</td>
                  <td>Varies by organization (SymptoPro, Couple to Couple League, others)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h3>Choosing a Method</h3>

          <p>No single FABM is best for every woman. The choice depends on a woman's health goals, cycle characteristics, comfort with different observation techniques, and whether she plans to work with an RRM physician. Women with PCOS or irregular cycles may benefit from the objectivity of the Marquette Method's hormonal monitoring. Women seeking the most direct connection to NaProTechnology diagnosis typically choose the Creighton Model. The SymptoThermal methods offer the redundancy of multiple biomarkers for confirmation.</p>

          <p>What matters most is that the method is learned from a trained instructor and charted consistently. The diagnostic value comes from the data. A well-kept chart gives the physician a window into hormonal function that no other tool can match.</p>

          <h3>Beyond Family Planning</h3>

          <p>FABMs are not just for couples trying to conceive or avoid pregnancy. Women who chart their cycles gain body literacy: an understanding of their own hormonal health that enables them to recognize when something changes. A cycle that was regular and suddenly becomes irregular is a signal. Premenstrual symptoms that worsen over time are a signal. These signals, captured on a chart, give physicians actionable data and give women an active role in their own healthcare.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6e">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>This is why RRM physicians consider charting the foundation of their practice. It is the starting point for diagnosis, the tool for monitoring treatment response, and the long-term record of a woman's reproductive health. Without it, the physician is, as one RRM doctor described it, "flying blind."<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2f">2</a></sup></p>

          <!-- Section 6: Conditions Treated -->
          <h2 id="conditions">Conditions Treated with Restorative Reproductive Medicine</h2>

          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Condition</th>
                  <th>How RRM Approaches It</th>
                  <th>Conventional Approach (for comparison)</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Endometriosis</td>
                  <td>Thorough diagnosis, excision surgery, long-term management plan</td>
                  <td>Hormonal suppression (birth control), ablation surgery, IVF to bypass</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>PCOS</td>
                  <td>Root-cause evaluation (insulin resistance, adrenal, inflammatory), targeted treatment</td>
                  <td>Birth control to regulate cycles, metformin, Clomid/letrozole for fertility</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Unexplained infertility</td>
                  <td>Advanced cycle-based diagnostics to identify previously missed causes</td>
                  <td>Empiric treatment with IUI or IVF without identifying the cause</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Recurrent miscarriage</td>
                  <td>Hormonal evaluation (progesterone, thyroid), immune factors, anatomical assessment</td>
                  <td>Progesterone supplementation, IVF with PGT-A</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Irregular or painful periods</td>
                  <td>Diagnostic workup to identify hormonal or structural cause, targeted treatment</td>
                  <td>Hormonal birth control to suppress symptoms</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Pelvic pain</td>
                  <td>Investigation for endometriosis, adhesions, or other structural causes</td>
                  <td>Pain management, hormonal suppression</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p><em>This content is for educational purposes only and does not constitute medical advice. Consult a qualified healthcare provider for diagnosis and treatment.</em></p>

          <!-- Section 7: RRM vs IVF -->
          <h2 id="rrm-vs-ivf">RRM vs. IVF: A Detailed Comparison</h2>

          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Factor</th>
                  <th>RRM</th>
                  <th>IVF</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Approach</td>
                  <td>Diagnose and treat root cause</td>
                  <td>Bypass reproductive system</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Goal</td>
                  <td>Restore natural function</td>
                  <td>Achieve pregnancy</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Treats underlying condition?</td>
                  <td>Yes</td>
                  <td>No</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Typical cost per cycle</td>
                  <td>Varies; often insurance-covered <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                  <td>$15,000&ndash;$30,000 per cycle <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Multiple pregnancy risk</td>
                  <td>Low (natural conception)</td>
                  <td>Higher (especially with multiple embryo transfer)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Best suited for</td>
                  <td>Treatable conditions (endometriosis, PCOS, hormonal issues)</td>
                  <td>Tubal blockage, severe male factor, when time is critical</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Published live birth rates</td>
                  <td>29&ndash;41% depending on age and diagnosis <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                  <td>~30&ndash;50% per cycle depending on age <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p>These approaches are not always mutually exclusive. Some patients benefit from RRM treatment before pursuing assisted reproduction, and some RRM practitioners work alongside fertility specialists. <a href="/courses/rrm-vs-ivf/">Learn more in our free course: RRM vs. Standard ART</a>.</p>

          <!-- Section 8: Evidence -->
          <h2 id="evidence">The Evidence Behind RRM</h2>

          <p>RRM is supported by peer-reviewed research published in journals including <em>Fertility and Sterility</em>, the <em>Journal of Restorative Reproductive Medicine</em>, and <em>BMC Pregnancy and Childbirth</em>. The <a href="https://library.rrmacademy.org">RRM Academy Research Library</a> contains 3,036+ peer-reviewed publications covering RRM outcomes, surgical techniques, hormonal protocols, and fertility awareness-based methods.</p>

          <p>Key findings from published research:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>RRM treatment followed by timed intercourse: 41% live birth rate <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE: JRRM 2021]</mark></li>
            <li>Surgical treatment of moderate-to-severe endometriosis: 55.3% pregnancy rate per woman <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE: meta-analysis]</mark></li>
            <li>RRM singletons had 3x fewer preterm deliveries compared to IVF <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></li>
            <li>Average cost of RRM medication cycles was 20x less than IVF <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE]</mark></li>
          </ul>

          <p><em>Note: Outcomes vary by individual. All statistics represent published research averages, not guarantees. <mark class="cite-needed">[CITE specific studies before publishing]</mark></em></p>

